title: For Sale/Trade:  Huldra Arms/CMMG 5.45x39 AR-15
postcontent: Ok so I did the math on this several times to make sure i wasn't short changing myself or over pricing. I believe my end result is a fair price. I have an AR-15 chambered in 5.45x39 and a little over 3K rounds of corrosive spam can ammo. Upper Huldra Arms Mark IV upper that's had 200 rounds through it (on a different lower) $639 new...my price $400. I took off a dollar a round, and keep in mind i have a magpul MOE hand guard with three rails ($40 and $10 per rail) as opposed to the standard hand guard. Lower is brand new ($270) CMMG with magpul MOE stock ($60) and rubber over mold grip ($21). Three steel mags (one still in plastic) one would have come with the upper so $40, and a Wolff extra power srping for the lower that I have not installed. Here's the tricky part...ammo. Different prices float out there for basic surplus ammo in this caliber, but i believe it's around .25 cents a round, but let's say it's .15 cents a round for the sake of a median. $450 worth of ammo. All that equals $1311. Since some out there might think I should shave it back a dollar or two I will arrive at my sale/ trade price of $1100 even. The upper has some slight wear and I tried to remove the flash hider to no avail so that's another reason i have to take some off the top. i would be willing to trade for a nice .45 and cash or a nice .357 (at least 4" barrel) and cash...but feel free to shoot me whatever, but please don't undervalue my rifle as I have carefully laid everything out. Pick up in Bossier/Shreveport only.

title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 52 International Match .22LR
postcontent:
This single shot target rifle has a 28 inch barrel. The barrel and the receiver are ornately engraved. There is a slight single discoloration in the bluing on the top of the barrel roughly halfway between the end of the stock and the end of the barrel. The beautiful curly maple free style thumb hole stock is near perfect, with the only notable flaw being a knot in the wood on the left hand side directly under the receiver. Included with this rifle are the front and rear Redfield Olympic model sights. This rifle has an adjustable buttstock. It comes with the forward hand stop, however the T-nut that anchors it to the lower rail is missing. The action is tight and the trigger is crisp. This rifle barely shows signs of use. 
The Model 52 was a bolt-action .22-caliber target rifle introduced by Winchester Repeating Arms in 1920 and is known as the “King of the .22's.” Field & Stream has called the Model 52 one of “the 50 best guns ever made.” The Model 52 was finally discontinued in 1980, but it remains as the Winchester historian, Herbert Houze, called it, “perfection in design.” The International Match version of the 52 is truly a work of art, and approximately only 300 were made. This is one of the models said to have been used in the Japanese Olympics. 
This rifle is in excellent condition and has been fired very little. It has spent most of its life in storage. This is truly a wonderful rifle for anyone's collection! Don't miss out on owning this magnificent King of the .22's! Please be sure to contact me with any questions you may have.
